<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF109-670-855  </DOCNO><DOCID>09 670 855.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Computerworld  Nov 19 1990 v24 n47 p134(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Systems managers crucial in computer crime prosecution.andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>Olenick, Lou.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Proving cases of computer crime can be difficult, and it isimportant for corporate information systems managers to be alertfor criminal activities and then to take the appropriate steps toinsure prosecution.andP;  The first step is to build a strong case thatwill convince upper management to take the problem seriously andpossibly hire an outside investigator.andP;  The evidence must bestrong in order to convince police to investigate and to see thecase through to trial.andP;  Managers must maintain audit trails ofcallback procedure, telephone records and of account/passwordidentification records.andP;  Managers must also be responsible forhandling the termination of an employee if it is an in-housecrime, and of securing the system against further tampering in thetime before trial.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     CompaniesLegal IssuesComputer crimesInvestigationsMethods.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>